> Am I correct in guessing that the application you're working on has made a call into another AppDomain at this point, either through remoting directly, or via SQL Server Management Objects?

Yes, we use remoting. Are you sure that the problem pops up only in remoting scenarios?

> Using a subclass of ObjectHandle that returns a custom ILease from InitializeLifetimeService() should fix this, as you suggest...

Ah, one more thing: a custom wrapper class or ObjectHandle descendant will need Serilog assembly in the target AppDomain to be deserialized. What if Serilog is not deployed there?

> figuring out how to keep the lease alive long enough without leaking the object entirely will need some thought. Anyone have any ideas?

If you're OK with custom wrapper class, then I'd suggest infinite lease time + explicit disconnection via RemotingServices.Disconnect, something like this:

```
// The original idea is by Nathan Evans, I believe
public class DisposableMarshalByRefObject : MarshalByRefObject, IDisposable
{
    public sealed override object InitializeLifetimeService()
    {
        return null;
    }

    private bool Disposed { get; set; }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        if (!Disposed)
        {
            Disposed = true;
            RemotingServices.Disconnect(this);
        }
    }
}
```

So now it's a question of where and when the wrapper should be disposed of. Perhaps it's when the stack of enrichers goes empty?

